Date: October 21, 2024
Objective: Second Round PCBway Orders
Record:

Main Ideas from Project Proposal:
Reinforced the importance of iterative testing and refinement in the PCB manufacturing process to achieve a reliable and efficient robotic assistant.

Reviewed additional datasheets for the LM1117 voltage regulator and Adafruit TB6612 motor driver breakout boards to ensure correct component integration in the Second Round PCB layout.
Diagrams and Schematics:

Submitted the Second Round PCBway Orders by 4:45 PM, incorporating all design modifications from the previous testing phase.
Design Problems and Decisions:

Voltage Stability Enhancements: Added additional decoupling capacitors near all voltage regulators to further stabilize power supply during dynamic loads.
Signal Trace Optimization: Adjusted PWM signal traces to minimize length and reduce potential signal reflections, enhancing signal integrity.

Calculated to achieve an impedance of approximately 50Î© to minimize reflections.
Documentation of Testing and Debugging Process:

Began assembling the power subsystems for the Car System, focusing on voltage regulation and stability.
Tested voltage outputs from the LM1117 regulators on the updated PCB layout to verify stability and adherence to specifications.
Important Notes for Debugging:

Ensure that all added decoupling capacitors are correctly soldered and placed close to their respective voltage regulator pins.
Verify that all signal traces meet impedance requirements to prevent signal integrity issues.
Analysis and Proposed Solutions for Debugging Problems:

Identified minor voltage drops during high-load testing and proposed increasing the trace width for power lines to reduce resistance.
Noted potential issues with servo motor torque under extended arm lengths and planned to implement additional power supply support.
Documentation of New Tests:

Scheduled to perform comprehensive voltage stability tests under maximum load conditions to validate the effectiveness of added decoupling capacitors.
Planned to use a network analyzer to test the impedance of signal traces and ensure compliance with design specifications.
Documentation of Final Performance Tests and Design Verification:

Scheduled full subsystem integration tests once the Second Round PCBs are received, ensuring that all components operate harmoniously and meet design requirements.
Topic Outlines for Reports:

Updated the Tolerance Analysis section to include the results from the Second Round PCBway Order tests, detailing the effectiveness of voltage stability enhancements and signal trace optimizations.







Date: October 22, 2024
Objective: Power Subsystem Development
Record:

Main Ideas from Project Proposal:
Focused on ensuring stable and reliable power delivery to all subsystems, crucial for the consistent operation of the robotic assistant.

Reviewed application notes on the LM1117 voltage regulator for optimal usage in high-current applications.
Studied best practices for implementing H-bridge motor drivers to ensure efficient and reliable motor control.
Diagrams and Schematics:

Finalized the Power Subsystem schematic, incorporating additional decoupling capacitors and heat dissipation solutions.
Design Problems and Decisions:

Heat Dissipation: Decided to incorporate aluminum heat sinks on all voltage regulators and motor drivers to manage thermal loads effectively.
Capacitor Placement: Strategically placed decoupling capacitors near power pins of all active components to enhance power stability and reduce noise.
Equations and Formulas:

Documentation of Testing and Debugging Process:

Assembled the power subsystems on the updated PCBs and connected them to the robotic arm components.
Tested voltage outputs under varying load conditions to ensure stability and compliance with specifications.
Documented voltage readings and observed thermal performance of voltage regulators and motor drivers.
Important Notes for Debugging:

Monitor temperature of heat sinks during initial testing to ensure effective heat dissipation.
Verify that all decoupling capacitors are properly connected to prevent power supply instability.
Analysis and Proposed Solutions for Debugging Problems:

Detected minor voltage fluctuations during load testing and proposed increasing the capacitance for enhanced filtering.
Observed slight overheating in motor drivers under prolonged operation and planned to implement additional cooling measures if necessary.
Documentation of New Tests:

Scheduled to perform extended load testing to evaluate the thermal performance of voltage regulators and motor drivers with heat sinks.
Planned to use thermal imaging to identify hotspots and optimize heat sink placement.
Documentation of Final Performance Tests and Design Verification:

Scheduled to integrate the power subsystems with the mechanical and control subsystems for comprehensive system testing in the upcoming weeks.
Topic Outlines for Reports:

Finalized the Tolerance Analysis section, detailing the effectiveness of power stability enhancements and thermal management solutions based on testing results.
